#: ../../docs/user_manual/working_with_mesh/mesh.rst:13
msgid "What's a mesh?"
msgstr ""

#: ../../docs/user_manual/working_with_mesh/mesh.rst:15
msgid ""
"A mesh is an unstructured grid usually with temporal and other "
"components. The spatial component contains a collection of vertices, "
"edges and/or faces, in 2D or 3D space:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../docs/user_manual/working_with_mesh/mesh.rst:19
msgid "**vertices** - XY(Z) points (in the layer's coordinate reference system)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../docs/user_manual/working_with_mesh/mesh.rst:20
msgid "**edges** - connect pairs of vertices"
msgstr ""

#: ../../docs/user_manual/working_with_mesh/mesh.rst:21
msgid ""
"**faces** - a face is a set of edges forming a closed shape - typically a"
" triangle or a quadrilateral (quad), rarely polygons with more vertices"
msgstr ""

#: ../../docs/user_manual/working_with_mesh/mesh.rst:24
msgid ""
"Relying on the above, mesh layers can thus have different types of "
"structure:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../docs/user_manual/working_with_mesh/mesh.rst:26
msgid ""
"1D Meshes: consist of vertices and edges. An edge connects two vertices "
"and can have assigned data (scalars or vectors) on it. The 1D mesh "
"network can be for example used for modelling of an urban drainage "
"system."
msgstr ""

#: ../../docs/user_manual/working_with_mesh/mesh.rst:29
msgid "2D meshes: consist of faces with triangles, regular or unstructured quads."
msgstr ""

#: ../../docs/user_manual/working_with_mesh/mesh.rst:30
msgid ""
"3D layered meshes: consist of multiple stacked 2D unstructured meshes "
"each extruded in the vertical direction (levels) by means of a vertical "
"coordinate. The vertices and faces have the same topology in each "
"vertical level. The mesh definition (vertical level extrusion) could in "
"general change in time. The data is usually defined in volume centres or "
"by some parametric function."
msgstr ""

#: ../../docs/user_manual/working_with_mesh/mesh.rst:41
msgid "Different mesh types"
msgstr ""

#: ../../docs/user_manual/working_with_mesh/mesh.rst:43
msgid ""
"Mesh provides information about the spatial structure. In addition, the "
"mesh can have datasets (groups) that assign a value to every vertex. For "
"example, having a triangular mesh with numbered vertices as shown in the "
"image below:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../docs/user_manual/working_with_mesh/mesh.rst:52
msgid "Triangular grid with numbered vertices"
msgstr ""

#: ../../docs/user_manual/working_with_mesh/mesh.rst:54
msgid ""
"Each vertex can store different datasets (typically multiple quantities),"
" and those datasets can also have a temporal dimension. Thus, a single "
"file may contain multiple datasets."
msgstr ""

#: ../../docs/user_manual/working_with_mesh/mesh.rst:58
msgid ""
"The following table gives an idea about the information that can be "
"stored in mesh datasets. Table columns represent indices of mesh "
"vertices, each row represents one dataset. Datasets can have different "
"datatypes. In this case, it stores wind velocity at 10m at a particular "
"moments in time (t1, t2, t3)."
msgstr ""

