msgid ""
":guilabel:`Split Selected Face(s)` (:guilabel:`Split Current Face`): "
"splits the face you are hovering over or each selected quad mesh faces "
"into two triangles"
msgstr ""

#: ../../docs/user_manual/working_with_mesh/mesh.rst:1181
msgid ""
":guilabel:`Delaunay Triangulation with Selected vertices`: builds "
"triangular faces using selected free vertices."
msgstr ""

#: ../../docs/user_manual/working_with_mesh/mesh.rst:1183
msgid ""
":guilabel:`Refine Selected Face(s)` (:guilabel:`Refine Current Face`): "
"splits the face into four faces, based on vertices added at the middle of"
" each edge (a triangle results into triangles, a quad into quads). Also "
"triangulates adjacent faces connected to the new vertices."
msgstr ""

#: ../../docs/user_manual/working_with_mesh/mesh.rst:1189
msgid "The edge markers"
msgstr ""

#: ../../docs/user_manual/working_with_mesh/mesh.rst:1191
msgid ""
"When the |meshDigitizing| :sup:`Digitize mesh elements` is active and you"
" hover over an edge, the edge is highlighted and it is possible to "
"interact with it. Depending on the context, following markers may be "
"available:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../docs/user_manual/working_with_mesh/mesh.rst:1195
msgid ""
"a **square**, at the center of the edge: click on it to select extremity "
"vertices."
msgstr ""

#: ../../docs/user_manual/working_with_mesh/mesh.rst:1196
msgid ""
"a **cross** if the two faces on either side can be merged: click on it to"
" delete the edge and merge the faces."
msgstr ""

#: ../../docs/user_manual/working_with_mesh/mesh.rst:1198
msgid ""
"a **circle** if the edge is between two triangles: Click on it to flip "
"the edge, i.e. connect it instead to the two other \"free\" vertices of "
"the faces"
msgstr ""

#: ../../docs/user_manual/working_with_mesh/mesh.rst:1202
msgid "The :guilabel:`Force by Selected Geometries` tool"
msgstr ""

#: ../../docs/user_manual/working_with_mesh/mesh.rst:1204
msgid ""
"The |meshEditForceByVectorLines| :sup:`Force by Selected Geometries` tool"
" provides advanced ways to apply break lines using lines geometry. A "
"break line will force the mesh to have edges along the line. Note that "
"the break line will not be considered persistent once the operation is "
"done; resulting edges will not act as constraints anymore and can be "
"modified like any other edge. This can be used for example to locally "
"modify a mesh layer with accurate lines, as river banks or border of road"
" embankments."
msgstr ""

#: ../../docs/user_manual/working_with_mesh/mesh.rst:1213
msgid ""
"Enable the |meshEditForceByVectorLines| :sup:`Force by Selected "
"Geometries` tool"
msgstr ""

#: ../../docs/user_manual/working_with_mesh/mesh.rst:1214
msgid "Indicate the geometry to use as \"forcing line\"; it can be:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../docs/user_manual/working_with_mesh/mesh.rst:1216
msgid ""
"picked from a line or polygon feature in the map canvas: right-click over"
" the vector feature and select it from the list in the contextual menu."
msgstr ""

#: ../../docs/user_manual/working_with_mesh/mesh.rst:1218
msgid ""
"a virtual line drawn over the mesh frame: left-click to add vertices, "
"right-click for validation. Vertices Z value is set through the "
":guilabel:`Vertex Z value` widget or the :guilabel:`z` widget if the "
":guilabel:`Advanced Digitizing Panel` is on. If the line is snapped to a "
"mesh vertex or a 3D vector feature's vertex or segment, the new vertex "
"takes the snapped element Z value."
msgstr ""

#: ../../docs/user_manual/working_with_mesh/mesh.rst:1225
msgid ""
"Mesh faces that overlap the line geometry or the polygon's boundary will "
"be affected in a way that depends on options you can set from the "
"|meshEditForceByVectorLines| :sup:`Force by Selected Geometries` tool "
"drop-down menu:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../docs/user_manual/working_with_mesh/mesh.rst:1230
msgid ""
"|checkbox| :guilabel:`Add new vertex on intersecting edges`: with this "
"option, a new vertex is added each time the forcing line intersect an "
"edge. This option leads to split along the line each encountered faces."
msgstr ""

#: ../../docs/user_manual/working_with_mesh/mesh.rst:1234
msgid ""
"Without this option, encountered faces are removed and replaced by faces "
"coming from a triangulation with only the existing vertices plus the "
"vertices of the forcing lines (new vertices are also added on the "
"boundary edge intersecting the forcing lines)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../docs/user_manual/working_with_mesh/mesh.rst:1244
msgid ""
"Force Mesh using a line geometry - Results without (middle) and with "
"(right) new vertex on edges intersection"
msgstr ""

#: ../../docs/user_manual/working_with_mesh/mesh.rst:1247
msgid ""
":guilabel:`Interpolate Z value from`: set how the new vertices Z value is"
" calculated. It can be from:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../docs/user_manual/working_with_mesh/mesh.rst:1250
msgid ""
"the :guilabel:`Mesh` itself: the new vertices Z value is interpolated "
"from vertices of the face they fall within"
msgstr ""

#: ../../docs/user_manual/working_with_mesh/mesh.rst:1252
msgid ""
"or the :guilabel:`Forcing line`: if the line is defined by a 3D vector "
"feature or a drawn line then the new vertices Z value is derived from its"
" geometry. In case of 2D line feature, the new vertices Z value is the "
":guilabel:`Vertex Z value`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../docs/user_manual/working_with_mesh/mesh.rst:1257
msgid ""
":guilabel:`Tolerance`: when an existing mesh vertex is closer to the line"
" than the tolerance value, do not create new vertex on the line but use "
"the existing vertex instead. The value can be set in :guilabel:`Meters at"
" Scale` or in :guilabel:`Map Units` (more details at "
":ref:`unit_selector`)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../docs/user_manual/working_with_mesh/mesh.rst:1266
msgid "Reindexing meshes"
msgstr ""

#: ../../docs/user_manual/working_with_mesh/mesh.rst:1268
msgid ""
"During edit, and in order to allow quick undo/redo operations, QGIS keeps"
" empty places for deleted elements, which may lead to growing memory use "
"and inefficient mesh structuring. The :menuselection:`Mesh -->` "
"|meshReindex| :menuselection:`Reindex Faces and Vertices` tool is "
"designed to remove these holes and renumber the indices of faces and "
"vertices so that they are continuous and somewhat reasonably ordered. "
"This optimizes relation between faces and vertices and increases the "
"efficiency of calculation."
msgstr ""

#: ../../docs/user_manual/working_with_mesh/mesh.rst:1277
msgid ""
"The |meshReindex| :guilabel:`Reindex Faces and Vertices` tool saves the "
"layer and clear the undo/redo stacks, disabling any rollback."
msgstr ""

#: ../../docs/user_manual/working_with_mesh/mesh.rst:1284
#: ../../docs/user_manual/working_with_mesh/mesh.rst:1295
msgid "Mesh Calculator"
msgstr ""

#: ../../docs/user_manual/working_with_mesh/mesh.rst:1286
msgid ""
"The :guilabel:`Mesh Calculator` tool from the top :menuselection:`Mesh` "
"menu allows you to perform arithmetic and logical calculations on "
"existing dataset groups to generate a new dataset group (see "
":numref:`figure_mesh_calculator`)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../docs/user_manual/working_with_mesh/mesh.rst:1297
msgid ""
"The :guilabel:`Datasets` list contains all dataset groups in the active "
"mesh layer. To use a dataset group in an expression, double click its "
"name in the list and it will be added to the :guilabel:`Mesh calculator "
"expression` field. You can then use the operators to construct "
"calculation expressions, or you can just type them into the box."
msgstr ""

#: ../../docs/user_manual/working_with_mesh/mesh.rst:1303
msgid ""
"The :guilabel:`Result Layer` helps you configure properties of the output"
" layer:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../docs/user_manual/working_with_mesh/mesh.rst:1305
msgid ""
"|checkbox| :guilabel:`Create on-the-fly dataset group instead of writing "
"layer to disk`:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../docs/user_manual/working_with_mesh/mesh.rst:1308
msgid ""
"If unchecked, the output is stored on disk as a new plain file. An "
":guilabel:`Output File` path and an :guilabel:`Output Format` are "
"required."
msgstr ""

#: ../../docs/user_manual/working_with_mesh/mesh.rst:1310
msgid ""
"If checked, a new dataset group will be added to the mesh layer. Values "
"of the dataset group are not stored in memory but each dataset is "
"calculated when needed with the formula entered in the mesh calculator. "
"That virtual dataset group is saved with the project, and if needed, it "
"can be removed or made persistent in file from the layer "
":guilabel:`Source` properties tab."
msgstr ""

#: ../../docs/user_manual/working_with_mesh/mesh.rst:1317
msgid ""
"In either case, you should provide a :guilabel:`Group Name` for the "
"output dataset group."
msgstr ""

#: ../../docs/user_manual/working_with_mesh/mesh.rst:1319
msgid "The :guilabel:`Spatial extent` to consider for calculation can be:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../docs/user_manual/working_with_mesh/mesh.rst:1321
msgid ""
"defined as a :guilabel:`Custom extent` using the :ref:`extent selector "
"<extent_selector>` widget."
msgstr ""

#: ../../docs/user_manual/working_with_mesh/mesh.rst:1322
msgid ""
"defined by a polygon layer (:guilabel:`Mask layer`) of the project: the "
"polygon features geometry are used to clip the mesh layer datasets"
msgstr ""

#: ../../docs/user_manual/working_with_mesh/mesh.rst:1324
msgid ""
"The :guilabel:`Temporal extent` to take into account for datasets can be "
"set with the :guilabel:`Start time` and :guilabel:`End time` options, "
"selected from the existing dataset groups timesteps. They can also be "
"filled using the :guilabel:`Use all selected dataset times` button to "
"take the whole range."
msgstr ""

#: ../../docs/user_manual/working_with_mesh/mesh.rst:1328
msgid ""
"With the |checkbox| :guilabel:`Add result to project` checkbox, the "
"result layer will automatically be added to the legend area and can be "
"visualized. Checked by default."
msgstr ""

#: ../../docs/user_manual/working_with_mesh/mesh.rst:1332
msgid ""
"The :guilabel:`Operators` section contains all available operators. To "
"add an operator to the mesh calculator expression box, click the "
"appropriate button. Mathematical calculations (``+``, ``-``, ``*``, ... )"
" and statistical functions (``min``, ``max``, ``sum (aggr)``, ``average "
"(aggr)``, ... ) are available. Conditional expressions (``=``, ``!=``, "
"``<``, ``>=``, ``IF``, ``AND``, ``NOT``, ... ) return either 0 for false "
"and 1 for true, and therefore can be used with other operators and "
"functions. The ``NODATA`` value can also be used in the expressions."
msgstr ""

#: ../../docs/user_manual/working_with_mesh/mesh.rst:1340
msgid ""
"The :guilabel:`Mesh Calculator Expression` widget shows and lets you edit"
" the expression to execute."
msgstr ""

